{"tag":"section","attrib":{"id":"ida81a429a-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"841"},"text":"§ 841.","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":" Art. 41. Challenges","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{"id":"ida81a429b-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/a"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"a"},"text":"(a)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"paragraph","attrib":{"id":"ida81a429c-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/a/1"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"1"},"text":"(1)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" The military judge and members of a general or special court-martial may be challenged by the accused or the trial counsel for cause stated to the court. The military judge shall determine the relevancy and validity of challenges for cause, and may not receive a challenge to more than one person at a time. Challenges by the trial counsel shall ordinarily be presented and decided before those by the accused are offered.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"paragraph","attrib":{"id":"ida81a429d-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/a/2"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"2"},"text":"(2)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" If exercise of a challenge for cause reduces the court below the number of members required by ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t10/s816"},"text":"section 816 of this title","children":[],"tail":" (article 16), all parties shall (notwithstanding "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t10/s829"},"text":"section 829 of this title","children":[],"tail":" (article 29)) either exercise or waive any challenge for cause then apparent against the remaining members of the court before additional members are detailed to the court. However, peremptory challenges shall not be exercised at that time."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{"id":"ida81a429e-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/b"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"b"},"text":"(b)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"paragraph","attrib":{"id":"ida81a429f-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/b/1"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"1"},"text":"(1)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" Each accused and the trial counsel are entitled initially to one peremptory challenge of members of the court. The military judge may not be challenged except for cause.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"paragraph","attrib":{"id":"ida81a42a0-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/b/2"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"2"},"text":"(2)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" If exercise of a peremptory challenge reduces the court below the number of members required by ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t10/s816"},"text":"section 816 of this title","children":[],"tail":" (article 16), the parties shall (notwithstanding "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t10/s829"},"text":"section 829 of this title","children":[],"tail":" (article 29)) either exercise or waive any remaining peremptory challenge (not previously waived) against the remaining members of the court before additional members are detailed to the court."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{"id":"ida81a42a1-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5","identifier":"/us/usc/t10/s841/c"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"c"},"text":"(c)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" Whenever additional members are detailed to the court, and after any challenges for cause against such additional members are presented and decided, each accused and the trial counsel are entitled to one peremptory challenge against members not previously subject to peremptory challenge.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"sourceCredit","attrib":{"id":"ida81a42a2-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5"},"text":"(","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1956-08-10/ch1041"},"text":"Aug. 10, 1956, ch. 1041","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/70A/51"},"text":"70A Stat. 51","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/90/632/s2/17"},"text":"Pub. L. 90–632, § 2(17)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1968-10-24"},"text":"Oct. 24, 1968","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/82/1339"},"text":"82 Stat. 1339","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/101/510/dA/tV/s541/b"},"text":"Pub. L. 101–510, div. A, title V, § 541(b)","children":[],"tail":"–(d), "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1990-11-05"},"text":"Nov. 5, 1990","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/104/1565"},"text":"104 Stat. 1565","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/111/383/dA/tX/s1075/b/13"},"text":"Pub. L. 111–383, div. A, title X, § 1075(b)(13)","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"2011-01-07"},"text":"Jan. 7, 2011","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/124/4369"},"text":"124 Stat. 4369","children":[],"tail":"; "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/114/328/dE/tLVII/s5224"},"text":"Pub. L. 114–328, div. E, title LVII, § 5224","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"2016-12-23"},"text":"Dec. 23, 2016","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/130/2909"},"text":"130 Stat. 2909","children":[],"tail":".)"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"notes","attrib":{"type":"uscNote","id":"ida81a42a3-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5"},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"historicalAndRevision","id":"ida81a42a4-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5"},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:table","attrib":{"width":"50%","id":"ida81a42a5-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5"},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:colgroup","attrib":{},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:col","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"html:col","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"html:col","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"html:thead","attrib":{},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:tr","attrib":{},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:th","attrib":{"colspan":"3"},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:span","attrib":{},"text":"Historical and Revision Notes","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"html:tr","attrib":{},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:th","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:i","attrib":{},"text":"Revised section","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":null},{"tag":"html:th","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:i","attrib":{},"text":"Source (U.S. Code)","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":null},{"tag":"html:th","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:i","attrib":{},"text":"Source (Statutes at Large)","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"html:tbody","attrib":{},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"html:tr","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:td","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:span","attrib":{},"text":"841(a)","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null},{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:span","attrib":{},"text":"841(b)","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":null},{"tag":"html:td","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":"50:616(a).","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":"50:616(b).","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null},{"tag":"html:td","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:p","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"html:a","attrib":{"href":"/us/act/1950-05-05/ch169/s1"},"text":"May 5, 1950, ch. 169, § 1","children":[],"tail":" (Art. 41), "},{"tag":"html:a","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/64/121"},"text":"64 Stat. 121","children":[],"tail":"."}],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"In subsection (a), the word “may” is substituted for the word “shall” before the words “not receive”.","children":[],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"In subsection (b), the word “the” is inserted before the word “trial”. The word “is” is substituted for the words “shall be”. The word “may” is substituted for the word “shall”.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"role":"crossHeading","topic":"editorialNotes","id":"ida81a42a6-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"b","attrib":{},"text":"Editorial Notes","children":[],"tail":null}],"tail":null}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"amendments","id":"ida81a42a7-3a6f-11f1-a58a-d8db54b14ab5"},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Amendments","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"2016—Subsec. (a)(1). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/114/328/s5224/1"},"text":"Pub. L. 114–328, § 5224(1)","children":[],"tail":", struck out “, or, if none, the court,” before “shall determine”."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsec. (a)(2). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/114/328/s5224/2"},"text":"Pub. L. 114–328, § 5224(2)","children":[],"tail":", struck out “minimum” after “below the”."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsec. (b)(2). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/114/328/s5224/3"},"text":"Pub. L. 114–328, § 5224(3)","children":[],"tail":", struck out “minimum” after “below the”."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"2011—Subsec. (c). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/111/383"},"text":"Pub. L. 111–383","children":[],"tail":" substituted “trial counsel” for “trail counsel”."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1990—Subsec. (a). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/101/510/s541/b"},"text":"Pub. L. 101–510, § 541(b)","children":[],"tail":", designated existing provision as par. (1) and added par. (2)."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsec. (b). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/101/510/s541/c"},"text":"Pub. L. 101–510, § 541(c)","children":[],"tail":", amended subsec. (b) generally. Prior to amendment, subsec. (b) read as follows: “Each accused and the trial counsel is entitled to one peremptory challenge, but the military judge may not be challenged except for cause.”"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsec. (c). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/101/510/s541/d"},"text":"Pub. L. 101–510, § 541(d)","children":[],"tail":", added subsec. (c)."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"1968—Subsec. (a). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/90/632/s2/17/A"},"text":"Pub. L. 90–632, § 2(17)(A)","children":[],"tail":", (B), inserted reference to the military judge and struck out references to the law officer of a general court-martial."}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"Subsec. (b). ","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/90/632/s2/17/C"},"text":"Pub. L. 90–632, § 2(17)(C)","children":[],"tail":", substituted “military judge” for “law officer”."}